history.content: I believe the only major difference is that stable marriage is not covered over the summer. I took it over the summer and it was a pretty good experience; it moves quite fast but it's nice to have just one class to focus on instead of having to juggle it with many other things over the semester (and some say the curve is also more generous over the summer).

children.subject: Also, it seems like it's easier to get a higher grade during the summer (but the material will be crammed into just a few weeks), so doing it during the summer given that you have a big reason/financial aid sounds good.

+1 I took it over summer and did not find it easier at all. In fact, it was very difficult for me to grasp complicated probability concepts that I had never learned before in less than 2 weeks. It was nice for me to declare and get out of the way over summer, but I definitely think I could have understood the concepts better, gotten a better grade, and not felt as stressed out if I took it during the semester.
(wrt the curve over the summer, it's not actually nicer--it just looks nicer because more people late drop during the summer than during the regular semester, and we have to take that into account.)
